You are likely referring to the fact that in TypeScript, there isn't a built-in "repeatable" type like in other languages. However, you can create a custom type or a class to achieve similar functionality.

Here's an example of how you can create a custom type to represent a repeatable value:

```typescript
class Repeatable<T> {
  private value: T;
  private repeatCount: number;

  constructor(value: T, repeatCount: number) {
    this.value = value;
    this.repeatCount = repeatCount;
  }

  get(): T[] {
    return Array(this.repeatCount).fill(this.value);
  }
}
```

You can then use this type like this:

```typescript
